ize: 14px; color: #999; font-style: italic;"></div> <i></i></div>
</div><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So he put about $3.8 million of his own =
(bonus) money into Archegos. That investment is now worth $0, since Archego=
s was vaporized. But shortly before he quit Archegos =E2=80=94=C2=A0on Marc=
h 30, 2021! =E2=80=94 it was worth=C2=A0<em>$30.5 million</em>, so that=E2=
=80=99s what he=E2=80=99s suing for:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">When he left Archegos, Sullivan requested the contents of his Individ=
ual Plan Account as of February 28, 2021.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">S=
ection 4.1 of the Elective Plan Contract and the =E2=80=9CDeferred Bonus Pa=
yment=E2=80=9D section of the Mandatory Plan Contract expressly provides fo=
r this 30 day =E2=80=9Clook back=E2=80=9D period, and requires that all def=
erred compensation be paid within thirty to sixty days of an employee=E2=80=
=99s departure from Archegos.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As of Februar=
y 28, 2021, Sullivan=E2=80=99s Individual Plan Account was valued at approx=
imately $30.5 million.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I love =
it so much. You work for a fund that gets vaporized, you comb through your =
contract, you=E2=80=99re like =E2=80=9Cwait I have a lookback option, they =
have to pay me as though=C2=A0they never got vaporized,=E2=80=9D so you=C2=
=A0quit immediately and=C2=A0<em>sue for $27 million of paper profits</em>.=
[3] The combination of chutzpah and careful contract reading!=C2=A0That=E2=
=80=99s about a 148% annual rate of return, $30.5 million on his $3.8 milli=
on of deferrals.[4] =E2=80=9CI worked at one of the best hedge funds in the=
 history of hedge funds, if you don=E2=80=99t count its final month, which =
I don=E2=80=99t, so give me my profits.=E2=80=9D[5] I hope every hedge fund=
 in the world is trying to hire this guy; this guy gets it.</p><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">My main question about Bill Hwang is always: <a href=3D"ht=
tps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28276298.281582/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3c=
uYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDQtMjcvYmlsbC1od2FuZy1hcn=
Jlc3QtaW5zaWRlLXRoZS12aWNpb3VzLWN5Y2xlLW9mLWFyY2hlZ29zLWNvbGxhcHNlP2NtcGlkP=
UJCRDA3MDUyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0=
dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDcwNSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cC21e54fae/email" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;"> What was he thinking</a>? The trade here =
was that Archegos borrowed a lot of money to buy a lot of a dozen stocks, t=
hose stocks went up because Archegos bought so much of them, Archegos borro=
wed more money against them to buy more of them, they kept going up, Archeg=
os kept being more levered, eventually a light breeze blew the whole thing =
over, Archegos got margin calls it couldn=E2=80=99t meet, the stocks were l=
iquidated and Archegos went to zero. It was obvious that this would happen,=
 and then it did, and Hwang is a sophisticated guy and it is hard to imagin=
e how he thought things would go. I still don=E2=80=99t know, but Sullivan=
=E2=80=99s lawsuit provides some (alleged) data points:</p><blockquote><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Through the fall of 2020, Sullivan and other Arche=
gos employees tried to understand the apparent shifts in Hwang=E2=80=99s tr=
ading strategy. Repeatedly, Sullivan inquired of Hwang and the Executive De=
fendants about the rationale for the ever-increasing positions in illiquid =
stocks, the amount of gross leverage being utilized, and what was being don=
e to ensure risks were properly managed and mitigated. =E2=80=A6</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Hwang and the Executive Defendants, in particular Hal=
ligan, Becker, and Mills, throughout this period misrepresented that Hwang=
=E2=80=99s new strategy was akin to =E2=80=9Cprivate equity in the public s=
ector,=E2=80=9D with Hwang attempting to portray himself as an activist inv=
estor seeking to accumulate large positions and exert pressure to force cha=
nges that would materially unlock substantial value. But this was a lie.</p=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Hwang had no such plan or intent. He had no t=
hesis to unlock value at any of these companies, and no research reflecting=
 any such thesis. The trading was not long-term value investing, but short-=
term day trading designed to use Archegos=E2=80=99 substantial leverage-dri=
ven buying power to manipulate the price of these illiquid stocks higher an=
d higher. Rather, Hwang reveled in these large positions, and gleefully tol=
d employees that this trading strategy allowed Archegos to =E2=80=9Cboss ar=
ound=E2=80=9D the executives of the companies it was investing in. On a mor=
e charitable day, Hwang would say he was influencing these companies in pos=
itive ways that reflected his religious ethics.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">In fact, unbeknownst to the Plan participants, Hwang=E2=80=99s claims =
were impossible because he accumulated the majority of these massive positi=
ons through swap agreements in which Archegos did not even hold those posit=
ions in its own name, had no voting rights, and could not meaningfully exer=
t pressure on those companies. Nor were his positions structured like priva=
te equity or activist investors, but instead relied on massive short-term m=
argin leverage that could be pulled on a moment=E2=80=99s notice.=C2=A0</p>=
</blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">None of that makes much sense, bu=
t it is not exactly competing with other explanations that do make sense. W=
as Hwang buying large chunks of big companies on swap (so without voting ri=
ghts) in order to boss around their executives to make them follow religiou=
s principles and become more valuable? I don=E2=80=99t think so, but I don=
=E2=80=99t know what I do think, so there you go.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">The complaint is also very funny=C2=A0on the question of, what=C2=A0=
<em>did=C2=A0</em>the analysts do all day?=C2=A0Apparently if they tried to=
 recommend stocks or discuss investment strategy=C2=A0=E2=80=94 which you m=
ight think would be the job? =E2=80=94=C2=A0Hwang would get mad and call=C2=
=A0them fat:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In this environmen=
t, Hwang and the Executive Defendants tolerated no questioning or even hint=
s of dissent. To enforce this culture, Hwang and the Executive Defendants p=
ublicly squashed even the slightest perceived challenges to his judgment, s=
trategy, and authority, often through very public rebukes and reprimands. F=
or example, if an employee raised questions about Hwang=E2=80=99s investmen=
t strategy or proposed an alternative privately, Hwang would often copy the=
 firm in a reply that disparaged and demeaned the employee and the employee=
=E2=80=99s thoughts. Other suspect employees were targeted with personal re=
criminations and criticisms about their physical appearances and personal b=
eliefs, especially religious beliefs. For example, Mills once told an emplo=
yee they could stand to =E2=80=9Cskip a few meals.=E2=80=9D During another =
dinner meeting, Hwang told an employee that they needed to lose weight.</p>=
</blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or here is a little story about A=
rchegos=E2=80=99s head of quantitative research:</p><blockquote><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">For example, in December 2020, at a firm wide meeting, th=
e Head of Quantitative Research Jensen Ko questioned why Hwang was buying t=
he same concentration of risky stocks every day. Hwang became visibly angry=
, scolding Jensen and telling him that he was =E2=80=9Cmisinformed=E2=80=9D=
 and should =E2=80=9Cpay attention=E2=80=9D and said =E2=80=9Cit=E2=80=99s =
not everyday Jensen.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
